      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "At the time, proponents defended redlining and segregation by arguing that racial segregation was a necessary social remedy to maintain public order and protect white families from the \"contagion\" of mixing with Black communities. Many believed that the de facto segregation existing in the North through living patterns had flowed down from the South and that \"hygiene laws\" were needed to supposedly improve the civic condition of the nation. Additionally, they framed these policies as a means to preserve desired community characteristics and property values, often claiming that segregation was superior to race-mixing without realizing they were systematically violating federal housing codes in their efforts to maintain it.",
